uction you would use [CODE: fastapi run] instead of...\n\nDocument 56:\nSource: docs\\help-fastapi.md\nNavigation: Help FastAPI - Get Help > Review Pull Requests > Tests\nContent: [Context: Help FastAPI - Get Help > Review Pull Requests > Tests]\n\n### Tests\n[ITALIC: Help me check that the PR has [BOLD:tests].\n] Check that the tests [BOLD:fail] before the PR.\n[ITALIC: Then check that the tests [BOLD:pass] after the PR.\n] Many PRs don't have tests, you can [BOLD:remind] them to add tests, or you can even [BOLD:suggest] some tests yourself. That's one of the things that consume most time and you can help a lot with that.\n- Then also comment what you tried, that way I'll know ...\n\nDocument 61:\nSource: docs\\tutorial\\testing.md\nNavigation: Testing > Separating tests > **FastAPI** app file\nContent: [Context: Testing > Separating tests > **FastAPI** app file]\n\n### [BOLD:FastAPI] app file\nLet's say you have a file structure as described in Bigger Applications:\n[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: . app [BOLD:init].py main.py...]\nIn the file [CODE: main.py] you have your [BOLD:FastAPI] app:\n{[ITALIC: ../../docs[ITALIC:src/app]testing/app[ITALIC:a]py310/main.py ]}...\n\nDocument 66:\nSource: docs\\tutorial\\testing.md\nNavigation: Testing\nContent: [Context: Testing]\n\n# Testing\nThanks to Starlette, testing [BOLD:FastAPI] applications is easy and enjoyable.\nIt is based on HTTPX, which in turn is designed based on Requests, so it's very familiar and intuitive.\nWith it, you can use pytest directly with [BOLD:FastAPI]....\n\nDocument 71:\nSource: docs\\index.md\nNavigation: FastAPI > Example > Run it\nContent: [Context: FastAPI > Example > Run it]\n\n### Run it\nRun the server with:\n\n[CODE[ITALIC:BLOCK]0: $ fastapi dev FastAPI CLI - Developmen...]\n\n\nAbout the command fastapi dev...\nThe command [CODE: fastapi dev] reads your [CODE: main.py] file automatically, detects the [BOLD:FastAPI] app in it, and starts a server using Uvicorn.\nBy default, [CODE: fastapi dev] wi